The paper discusses the use of coding theory in designing efficient random access protocols for machine-to-machine communications. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) or Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper also discusses the use of successive interference cancellation, which falls under the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of erasure-correcting codes, which is a topic covered in the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the design of access protocols using graph theory, which is a topic covered in the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.IT and cs.NI, followed by cs.SY, cs.CR, and cs.DS.
